questionTemplates.text:
M: Hello, Jane. I really want to know something about Mary. Do you know how can I get in touch with her?
W: Peter, you can try this telephone number.
{a}

M: I think I'm going to give up playing tennis. I lost again today.
W: Just because you lost? It that the reason to quit?
{a}

M: Why didn't you make a birthday cake for Peter?
W: Because I didn't have enough butter and you weren't here to buy any. I really had my hands full.
{a}

M: Shall we meet at ten o'clock?
W: I'm afraid it's too late. Let's make it thirty minutes earlier.
{a}

M: What are you going to have, Helen?
W: Just a hamburger. What about you?
{a}

W: How come you were late this morning, Tom?
M: I'm sorry, Mrs Smith, but I had a stomachache.
{a}

W: Have you seen my book anywhere?
M: Yes, they are on your bed.
{a}

F: Would you mind if I turn the radio off?
M: Not at all.
{a}

M: The train leaves every 30 minutes. You're five minutes late for the 7:30 train.
W: Sorry, I have to catch the next train.
{a}

M: There are only 13 chairs for 14 of us.
W: Why not find another, then?
{a}

W: Yesterday I met Mike in the street.
M: It's impossible. He left for London the day before yesterday and hasn't come back yet.
{a}

W: If the weather is this hot tomorrow, we may as well give up the idea of playing tennis in the afternoon.
M: Oh, I don't think it'll last long. The weather forecast says it will cloud over by mid-afternoon
{a}

W: I hear you like apple best.
M: Next to banana.
{a}

W: I'd like to buy these two chairs. How much are they?
M: They are 45 dollars each or 80 dollars for the pair.
{a}

M: Hello, can I speak to Mrs. Smith, please?
W: Speaking.
{a}

W: You look tired.
M: It's been a really busy week. People have been borrowing so many books. This always happens around examination time.
{a}

M: Shawn's been trying for months to find a job. But I wonder how he could get a job when he looks like that.
W: Oh, that poor guy! He really should shave himself every other day at least and put on something clean.
{a}

M: I hope you can understand my reasons for deciding to leave, Mrs. Harrison.
W: Do I have to remind you that we have invested a lot of time and money in your career here?
{a}

W: Ray, are you going straight home after school today?
M: No. I have a class until 1 o'clock, and after that I'm going to spend a couple of hours at the library before going home.
{a}

F: Which do you like better, horse riding or driving a car?
M: I prefer horse riding to driving a car.
{a}

W: I thought Tom said he got A's in all his tests.
M: Mary, you should know better than to take Tom's words too seriously.
{a}

M: Though we didn't win the game, we were satisfied with our performance.
W: You did a great job. You almost beat the world's champions. It's a real surprise to many people.
{a}

W: Is this your book, Mike?
M: No, it isn't mine. It's Sam's.
{a}

M: When did you see the American film?
F: I saw it after school.
{a}

W: When is the earliest train to Beijing?
M: There is one at six, and if that is full, there is another at seven.
{a}

M: Hi, Jane. So glad to see you again.
W: Likewise. I remember the last time we wet was 5 months ago at Mike's birthday party. How are you doing?
{a}
